<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan People Have Final Say on Tibet Issue: Official (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wolf also elaborated the religious situation, saying that
"(Tibetan) people, religion and culture will continue to grow
fainter and could one day disappear."
</P>
<P>
Raidi said that, in truth, "China's national policy of freedom
in religious belief has been strictly implemented in Tibet."
According to him, the central government in recent years allocated
more than 200 million yuan to renovate and support 1,700 sites of
worship, including the Potala Palace, Johkang Monastery,
Gandian Monastery, and Samyai Monastery.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has over 46,000 monks and nuns and they can freely
carry out their religious activities, he said. "There are
followers praying with prayer wheels in hand in all major
monasteries in Lhasa and no one interferes in their activities,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Raidi also spoke on the importance of improving the management
on religious activities in accordance with the law. "We will not
allow religions to interfere with the administrative and judicial
matters, education and marriage affairs. Moreover, it is also
prohibited blackmailing or endangering the lives and property of
the people in the name of religion, and the abolished feudal
privileges are also not permitted to be resumed," Raidi added.
</P>
<P>
"The reason to crack down on activities held by the separatists
who are acting under cover of religion is to protect the majority
of the religious believers and ensure that the religious
activities are carried out in line with the doctrines," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Dalai Lama and his associates, Raidi said the
separatist group led by the Dalai Lama had become the anti-China
tool ever since they betrayed the motherland and moved to live in
exile in 1959.
</P>
<P>
He never concerned himself with the real life of the Tibetan
people and did nothing beneficial for Tibet. The Tibetan people,
thus far, are now aware of his separatist theory and have long
abandoned him, Raidi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan People Have Final Say on Tibet Issue: Official (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the development of the Tibetan culture, Raidi said both the
Constitution of the People's Republic of China and the Law on
Regional Autonomy of China's Minority Nationalities have
explicitly set out provisions demanding that the ethnic culture in
the Tibet Autonomous Region be respected, protected and advanced.
</P>
<P>
"Our ethnic culture is progressing at an unprecedented pace for
the present, and the Tibetan language is widely used in the
autonomous region, since the central government has full respect
for the Tibetan language and makes every effort to protect it,"
Raidi said.
</P>
<P>
All the regulations, resolutions, documents, and media reports
in Tibet appear in two languages, Chinese and Tibetan, according
to Raidi.
</P>
<P>
The region also drafted special regulations to encourage wider
use of the local language, and has also set up special
institutions for exclusive research on the Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
According to Raidi, marked achievements have been scored in the
language research, and also in discovering and and preserving
Tibet's exquisite cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
For example, tens of thousands of copies of The King Gesser, an
ancient Tibetan folk epic, have been published in Tibet, with more
scheduled to come out in the future.
</P>
<P>
"All these are clear indications that the Tibetan culture is
progressing by the day instead of growing fainter and could one
day disappear as Frank Wolf predicted," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Facts speak louder than words," Raidi said. "All the changes
that took place in Tibet over the past forty-plus years have been
known not only by people with a sense of justice, even those
officials with the former Tibet government are also truly
convinced after they returned from exile and saw the changes."
</P>
<P>
"But the anti-China forces in the United States and other
Western nations, out of a desire to split China and destroy the
national unity of the Chinese people, have always schemed to look
for a bone in an egg, confound right and wrong, and confuse and
poison people's minds regardless of the the happy lives the
Tibetan people are leading," added the chairman.
</P>
<P>
"And that also explains why US congressman Frank Wolf should
slip into Tibet stealthily and afterwards launch a malicious
attack to vilify the Tibetan people," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan people will always open their arms to friendly
visitors of all kinds, but those who spread lies out of hostility
and maliciousness will be unwelcome in the region, Raidi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
