<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, United States into Hong Kong Beach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- World number one Brazil and
Olympic champions United States both qualified for the semi-finals
after they finished as winners of the two quarter-final groups at
the on-going Kent Beach Volleyball Grand Slam in the Victoria Park
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The semi-finals and final of the four-day event are all set for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, in Group A, took the top spot after their 2-0 wins over
China, Japan and Australia here today while Australia, who, after
losing to Brazil, beat Japan and China 2-0, took the second place.
</P>
<P>
China won over Japan 2-0 but lost to Brazil and Australia both
in 2-0 and thus finished third in the group and winless Japan were
fourth and last.
</P>
<P>
In Group B, the United States, who scored 2-0 wins over Mexico,
South Africa and New Zealand, won the group's top position.
Mexico, with 2-0 wins over New Zealand and South Africa and one
loss to the United States, finished as the runners-up.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand and South Africa were third and fourth of the
group.
</P>
<P>
The top two teams of the two groups advanced into the
semi-finals slated for Sunday, with Brazil playing Mexico and
Australia taking on United States in the morning and the final is
slated for Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The third and fourth placers of the groups are to play for the
fifth to eighth placers, also on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The most impressive match in the Plate category today was
probably that between Hong Kong and India, which Hong Kong won.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in history that any Hong Kong team had
ever won a beach volleyball match. The four joyful players sprayed
soft drinks on each other in post-match celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy for this historical victory. We won the match
by playing a clever game against the Indians," said the team's
coach Cheng King Leung.
</P>
<P>
"The Indians are taller and we could not win just by spiking.
So I asked my players to switch to fast attacks, which worked," he
added.
</P>
<P>
China, who finished fifth last year, faces New Zealand tomorrow
for the fifth place and Japan meet South Africa for the seventh
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
