<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Visit Japan, S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu will leave tonight on his first visit to
Japan and South Korea to deepen trade and economic ties with the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
During his week-long visit, Netanyahu will be accompanied by
Finance Minister Ya'acov Ne'eman, his office's director-general
Avigdor Lieberman, his diplomatic adviser Uzi Arad's and a large
delegation of leading Israeli businessmen.
</P>
<P>
On his way to Tokyo, Netanyahu will have a brief refueling
stop in the Chinese capital city of Beijing, and on the way home,
he is to stop over in Baku of Azerbaijan to meet senior
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's first far east trip came at a time of deepening
diplomatic isolation since the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
came to a halt due to Israeli building of the controversial Har
Homa settlement in East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Israel has also been criticized internationally for imposing
tough sanctions against the Palestinians after the July 30 twin
suicide bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, which
killed 16 people and further chilled the Israeli-Palestinian
relations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Japanese officials have been making punctilious
preparations for Netanyahu's two-day visit to Japan. The
Japanese hosts have been astounding their Israeli counterparts
by insisting on strict observance of diplomatic protocol at
every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
Months of preliminary work have been invested by both
countries in an effort to make Netanyahu's trip a political and
economic success.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the discussion of increasing trade between
Israel and Japan, Netanyahu is expected to talk about the issue
of Japan's effort to gain acceptance as a permanent member of
the United Nations Security Council and its impact on the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is scheduled to arrive at Seoul next Wednesday for
a two-day visit to South Korea. Two bilateral agreements will be
signed during the visit, one on agricultural cooperation and the
other on telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-South Korean trade has been expanding rapidly in
recent years to 700 million U.S. dollars in 1996 from only 100
million dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade already totaled 450 million dollars during
the first half of this year, with a prospective trade of one
billion dollars for the whole year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
