<HEADLINE> AL Criticizes Israeli Plans to Build Dam on Yarmuk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League today strongly
criticized the decision of the Israeli government to build a dam
on Al Yarmuk river which Syria wants to restore.
</P>
<P>
Zakraia Ismail, AL Assistant Secretary General for Political
Affairs, said this decision represents "a new chapter in the
series of provocations and blackmailing practiced by Israel."
</P>
<P>
He believed that these Israeli policies which conflict with UN
Security Council resolutions and the land for peace principle will
be doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
"It is noteworthy that the spokesman of the Israeli
Infrastructure Ministry said the decision to move the site of the
dam inside the demilitarized zone was taken for technical
reasons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Maariv newspaper reported on Friday that Israel is
planning to establish a dam on the Yarmuk river, which runs across
the southern Golan Heights, occupied by Israel since 1967.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binjamin Netanyahu has approved a
relevant proposal by Minister of Infrastructure Ariel Sharon,
reversing another decision taken by late Premier Yitzhak Rabin on
establishing the dam in a region further in the south, said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been frozen since Netanyahu
resumed power in May 1996. Netanyahu rejected Damascus' insistence
on full Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights in return for
full peace with the Jewish state, as verbally agreed by the
previous Labor government. 
</P>
