<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between Israeli troops
and Lebanese Hezbullah guerrillas erupted again today in south
Lebanon as the ceasefire monitoring committee is deliberating the
complaints by Israel and Lebanon of truce violations.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese official National News Agency reported that
today's fighting mainly focused on the the western and central
sectors of the Israeli-established "security zone" in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Israeli warplanes fired at least
six air-to-surface missiles in three sorties over the areas near
the village of Yater and between Jbal el Batm and Zabqine in
the western sector of the border enclave at 9:10 am (6:10
GMT) and 11:00 am (8:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Besides the air raids, Israeli troops also bombarded the same
areas with 120 mm and 155 mm shells at 10:00 am (7:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The clashes between the guerrillas of Hezbullah, or Party of
God, and Israeli troops, which took place in three other areas in
the western sector of the buffer zone today, lasted several hours.
</P>
<P>
The casualties of the clash were not officially announced, but
the Hezbullah said in its statement that the battle caused death
and injury to the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Naqoura, just near the sites of fighting, the
five-nation ceasefire monitoring committee is deliberating the
complaints of truce violations presented by Lebanon and Israel
after three consecutive days of meeting.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made up of the delegates from the United States,
France, Israel, Syria and Lebanon and established after last
year's 16-day blitz of Lebanon by Israel, was unable to reach a
consensus over whether or not Israel should be blamed for
Monday's shelling of the Lebanese port city of Saida where nine
civilians were killed and nearly 40 others wounded. 
</P>
