<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Imported Beef Free of Bacteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Examination result showed
that Kuwait's imported frozen beef from the United States was not
contaminated by the deadly E. Coli bacteria, easing fears of the
local people, a Kuwaiti health official said today.
</P>
<P>
Al-Saif, assistant undersecretary at Kuwaiti Health Ministry
for community health affairs said "all meat samples, processed or
unprocessed, imported from the United States proved free of any
bacteria."
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Health Ministry and Kuwait Municipality took
samples on August 18 from all shops, stores and supermarkets that
deal in meat imported from the U.S. and sent the samples to
laboratories of the ministry for examination following reports of
the issue floated in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agriculture Department ordered a couple of weeks ago
that a huge amount of frozen beef be withdrawn from the market
for fear that they were contaminated with deadly E. Coli
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Al-Saif said that the ministry had been following up the
E. Coli bacteria issue with the World Health Organization since
it was reported, stressing that the ministry's laboratories are
extremely effective and reliable.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy director of the nutrition department at the
Kuwaiti Municipality Jaman Al-Hajri said that authorities
regularly takes samples of all imported food products for tests
to make sure they are fit for human consumption.
</P>
<P>
He said additional samples of beef were also attained to
double check that they are free from the said bacteria, which
leads to kidney failure and ultimately death.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait imports food products from many foreign countries,
including the U.S. Australia and European states. All kinds of
imported food supplies are always subject to inspection before
reaching consumers in the Gulf state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
