<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Jordan to Build Dam on Yarmouk River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 23 (Xinhua) - Jordan announced today it will
build a dam on the Yarmouk River to get the share of water it
deserves to help solve water shortage problem.
</P>
<P>
An official spokesman, who declined to be named, made the
statement after recent media reports that Israel is planning to
build its own dam at upper reaches of the same river in order to
crash Jordan's pursuit for more water, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will construct a dam at Aladasia to divert its share of
the Yarmouk water to the King Abdullah Channel, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Everything has been ready for the project which is totally
financed by Jordan itself and can save water from the river to
serve its people after being finished, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 1994 peace treaty between Jordan and Israel includes
provision to construct such a dam on the Yarmouk River, which
mainly crosses the border between Israel and Syria and spreads
branches into the territory of Jordan, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Jordan is committed to implement the articles
agreed by both sides in a way that does not affect the interests
of any third party.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was surprised by media reports that Israel plans to
construct a dam on the Yarmouk River in Elahama in consent with
Jordan. The spokesman denied such a claim.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he added, the Jordanian government has not and
will not enter any agreements or negotiations with Israel that
will affect the results of peace negotiations between any Arab
country and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Shortage of water has been a problem for most of the Arab
countries in the Middle East and Israel. Jordan has always been
pursuing water in various ways as it is far below the water-poor
country line of 1,000 cubic meters per capita per year.
</P>
<P>
Jordan shares most of its surface water resources with
neighboring countries but had been deprived of its fair share,
resulting in severe shortage of the country's water supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
