<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 23 (Xinhua) - Dialogues for compromise continued
here today between the Jordanian government and some opposition
parties that declared to boycott the Parliamentary elections to
be held in November.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir
Mutawe' affirmed this today after a cabinet meeting chaired by
Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe' also said that another meeting is to take place
this week between the government and the opposition parties
to settle the disputes that arose last month as altogether
six opposition parties have claimed to boycot the elections.
</P>
<P>
The parties sticked to their position after the government
decided to hold elections, citing the Press and Publication Law,
the one-person-one-vote election system, the normalization of ties
with Israel and the government`s measures to marginalize political
parties as the main reasons behind their boycott.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties now make up 23 seats in the 80-member
Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Multi-party system was revived in the country in 1989 as
part of the political reforms launched after widespread riots
set off by economic hardships. 
