<HEADLINE> Emergency Rule to Be Lifted in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will remove the
10-year-old emergency rule in southeastern Turkey by early next
year, Deputy Prime Minister Ismet Sezgin announced today.
</P>
<P>
"Emergency rule will be lifted either at the end of this year
or at the start of 1998," Sezgin was quoted as saying by the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Emergency rule has been imposed in nine southeastern provinces
since 1987, giving soliders and police more extensive powers of
arrest and detention in the fight against the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Reliable official sources said that Turkey made the move
because the task of fighting the PKK has been basically completed
and there is no need to keep the emergency rule in those areas.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also Defense Minister, said that the village guard
system, which was established to counter the PKK, will continue
their function in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has employed more than 60,000 militia
in the village guard, but these guards have been accused by the
media of involvement in extortion, drug trafficking and other
illegal matters.
</P>
<P>
The PKK existence has long been termed as the most dangerous
threat to the border security of southeastern Turkey, leading to a
large scale military campaign in mid-May by the Turkish troops in
northern Iraq where PKK have taken shelter and launched
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
More than 26,000 people, including soldiers, rebels and
civilians, have been killed in the 13-year-old separatist war by
the PKK fighting for an independent Kurdish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
