<HEADLINE> World Bank Suggests Restructure of Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) today
suggested that the Tanzanian government restructure the country's
power sector to make it financially viable.
</P>
<P>
The WB Regional Vice-President for Africa, Callisto Madavu,
told local reporters in Dar es Salaam that such a move is
necessary as at present the situation is that most power
consumers, including government and parastatal institutions do
not pay for the energy provided them by the Tanzania Electric
Supply Company (TANESCO).
</P>
<P>
Now, various government institutions owe TANESCO 12.1 billion
shillings (20 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Once the power sector is restructured, people, including
parastatal organizations will be able to pay for the power they
consume, Madavu said, and adding, "...our aim is to put the power
company on sound financial footing."
</P>
<P>
The WB position, however, has irked industrialists and power
consumers who complain that the move would burden them since
electricity is now the basic utility for Tanzanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
