<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Says All Tribes Equal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government said
today that tendancies by some tribes to feel more superior than
others are a recipe of ethnic tension and division in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Local government and housing minister Bennie Mwiinga said here
today that Zambia is a unitary state and no tribe is superior
over others.
</P>
<P>
At the eighth freedom forum he said no ethnic group has the
right to redicule another ethnic group because no one has a
choice to be born in a particular tribe.
</P>
<P>
The minister accused some pliticians of making tribal politics
their career and ending up dividing the nation in their quest for
political power at all costs.
</P>
<P>
He noted intermarriages, urbanization and good government
policies have contributed to the creation of a strong ethnic
society which can not be easily broken.
</P>
<P>
Tetani Banda, leader of the National Democratic Party, said at
the forum that there is need to put in place deliberate policies
that will ensure tribal balancing in the various organs of the
country to maintain peace and stability in the multi-ethnic
society like Zambia with 72 tribes. 
</P>
