<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10th World Conference on Tobacco and Health Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said smoking control work should be promoted as part of China's
efforts to improve health levels and keep pace with the country's
economic development and social progress.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has adopted a number of laws and
regulations designed to promote smoking control efforts
disseminate related information to the general public," Jiang told
conferees attending the opening session of the international
anti-smoking conference which opened here in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The country has strictly banned smoking amongst minors and
students in primary and middle schools. He added that adult
smokers are being persuaded to quit the habit and live a healthy
life.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, "China will continue to engage in concerted
efforts with other countries to improve the health of the people."
</P>
<P>
"I hope the World Health Organization (WHO) will make further
contributions to the global smoking control drive," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session, WHO director general hiroshi
Nakajima said that tobacco is not only a big health problem but
also the cause for a loss of several billion US dollars in the
world each year.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, he added, so many societies in the world still
regard the tobacco consumption as acceptable social behavior.
He said that WHO will possibly work out the framework for
an interantional tobacco control convention after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The conference is the first of its kind held in China, a
country which is home to 320 million smokers and a giant tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,800 delegates from China and 103 other countries and
regions attended the opening session held in the Great Hall of
the People.
</P>
<P>
China's Health Minister Chen Minzhang and the Soong Ching Ling
Foundation were awarded WHO Tobacco or Health medals for their
remarkable achievements in fighting for a smoke-free society.
</P>
<P>
WHO Director General Hiroshi Nakajima and officials from WHO,
Unicef and various other international organizations also attended
the conference.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the opening session, the Chinese president met with
and had a picture taken with some conferees
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference, with the theme "Tobacco: The Growing
Epidemic," will focus on the tobacco industry's expansion into
developing countries, as well as smoking control, new methods to
help people quit smoking, passive smoking, and the effects of
tobacco on women and young people.
</P>
<P>
A total of 95 symposiums and an exhibition will be held in the
Beijing International Conference Center, the main venue of the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair, Adams to Meet on Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is preparing to meet Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams within the next
few weeks in a historic move which will set the seal on Sinn
Fein's involvement in full-scale negotiations on the future of
Northern Ireland, The Sunday Telegraph reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the highly sensitive first meeting
between a British Prime Minister and Sinn Fein's president is seen
by the Government as the inevitable consequence of the decision,
to be announced this week, to allow Adams and colleagues to join
all-party talks next month.
</P>
<P>
Marjorie Mowlam, secretary of state for Northern Ireland, will
complete her assessment within the next few days of whether the
Irish Republican Army (IRA) ceasefire declared on July 19 is
"genuine in word and deed."
</P>
<P>
Although she insisted last night that she would not take a
formal decision until she has been briefed this week by the Army
and other security forces, there is no doubt in Northern Ireland
or elsewhere that the IRA has met the Government's six-week test.
</P>
<P>
Blair will not meet Adams until after Sinn Fein has joined the
formal talks, due to begin on September 15, and publicly signed up
to the six "Mitchell principles" on the decommissioning of
terrorist weapons, likely to come on the same day.
</P>
<P>
But the Government has made clear that a meeting is likely to
follow within weeks. In a letter last month to Martin McGuinness,
Sinn Fein's chief negotiator, Ms Mowlam said meetings with Mr
Blair "would be dealt with on the same basis as for other
participants" once Sinn Fein had joined negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mr Blair has met the leaders of other Northern Ireland parties
regularly in Downing Street, and has never refused a request to do
so. A Northern Ireland Office insider said yesterday: "The Prime
Minister has never not been in the business of meeting party
leaders." A senior minister said: "A meeting with Gerry Adams
will happen at some point."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
