<HEADLINE> Minister: Tension Grips South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Information Minister
Bassem Al-Sabaa said today tension and apprehension were seizing
the towns and villages in south Lebanon due to Israeli policies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio, he said
that there was an Israeli plan aimed at driving a wedge between
the resistance forces and the Lebanese people and dragging
Lebanon back to internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Israel will never have fulfilled its objectives because Lebanon
has past the stage of being lured into domestic strifes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops killed three Hezbollah (Party of God) guerrillas
in south Lebanon Saturday in fierce clashes that included air
raids and artillery exchange.
</P>
<P>
The violence capped the worst week in south Lebanon's
cross-border violence since a cease-fire understanding ended a
17-day Israeli blitz on Lebanon in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sabaa referred to the April understanding between Israel and
Lebanon as an "accepted mechanism" to protect civilians in the
south.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese minister lashed out at the Israeli government of
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and accused it of being the
cause behind the tension in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon believes that peace to be reached should be based on
the implementation by Israel of U.N. Security Council resolution
425, which demands the withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern
Lebanon..." he said.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 Israeli troops have held a border occupation in a
self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon since 1985, in
defiance of U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
