<HEADLINE> Russian PM Stresses Ties With Belarus Despite Recent Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said today that his country will strengthen ties with
Belarus despite a recent row over the detainment of Russian
journalists there.
</P>
<P>
"We shall do everything to strengthen our ties with Belarus.
They are too precious, too important for us all," Chernomyrdin was
quoted by the Interfax news agency as saying while visiting the
Moscow International Air Show.
</P>
<P>
Six journalists from Russia's ORT television were detained
recently in Belarus after filming on the Belarussian-Lithuanian
border.
</P>
<P>
Three Russian journalists were released this week but three
other journalists, who are Belarussian citizens, remain in jail
pending trial for allegedly trying to violate the Belarussian
border.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax also quoted a senior official in the Kremlin as
saying that Russian President Boris Yeltsin had demanded on
Saturday that the three Belarussian journalists also be freed.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin criticized Belarus for detaining the journalists,
saying such moves were "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
But the Russian premier said a union treaty signed this year by
the two former Soviet republics was much more important.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Belarus signed a treaty in May calling for closer
economic, political and military ties but both nations retain full
sovereignty and the treaty has had little practical effect.
</P>
<P>
Belarus, sandwiched among Russia, Ukraine and Poland, has
enjoyed close bond with Russia. Most of the 10 million
Belarussians hope that the union with some 150 million Russians
could end their country's economic difficulty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
