<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Denies Firing at Ex-president </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police today denied that
the police fired at ex-president Kenneth David Kaunda who tried
to address an opposition rally Saturday in central town of Kabwe,
the Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Standwell Lungu also denied that the police
fired bullets at Kaunda's supporters to disrupt the rally.
</P>
<P>
The police only used " tear gas cannisters" to disperse the
people, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said that Kaunda, President of the United
National Independence Party (UNIP), and another oppisition leader
Roger Chongwe were shot by police while they were driving away
from a UNIP's local headquaters after being prevented from
addressing the rally.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zambia News Agency said that Kaunda was last
night hospitalized at Kabwe General Hospital, while Chongwe went
under an emergency operationn to remove a bullet from the neck.
</P>
<P>
Several other senior UNIP officials were also injured in the
confusion and admitted to the hospital, said sources close to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Both Kaunda and Chongwe were reported to be out of danger and
that they were discharged and driven to Lusaka during the early
hours of this morning.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today, Deputy Minister Alfred Chambeshi
of Central Province, of which Kabwe is the capital, regretted the
use of live ammunition by police in an attempt to disperse the
opposition rally while defending the police action.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the situation in Kabwe has returned to
normal with street vendors going about with their business
activities. However, a few armed policemen are deployed in
strategic places in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
