<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Wins Belgian Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Rainmaster Michael Schumacher
of Germany lived up to his reputation today by winning the
Formula-One grand prix at the rain-lashed Spa-Francorchamps
circuit.
</P>
<P>
It was the German's third consecutive win in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the third position on the grid behind Jacques
Villeneuve of Canada and Jean Alesi of France, Schumacher clocked
an accumulated winning time of one hour 33 minutes 46.717 seconds
for the 44-lap, 306.577-kilometer circuit, averaging 196.149
kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher once built up a leading gap of more than 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The win added a full 10 points to Schumacher's tally which
increased to 66 points for this year's world championship while
his team Ferrari also got 10 points to 54 points on the team
standings.
</P>
<P>
Giancarlo Fisichella from Italy and Mika Hakkinen of Finland,
fourth and fifth out of the starting grid, held on to finish
runner-up and third out of a field of 22 starters.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen was reinstated in the fifth spot on the grid after his
team McLaren appealed against a decision to put him to the back of
the grid for alleged fuel irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The Finn's team said that the fuel was unchanged since the
British grand prix where samples of the fuel were tested and found
to be legal.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve, who grabbed the pole position after winning
Saturday's qualifying round with a lap time of 1:49.450, gave up
the leader's position after three laps of race.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian driver later battled back from 14th place to
finish sixth.
</P>
<P>
Damon Hill of Britain, who won the Belgian stop of the grand
prix circuit back-to-back in 1993 and 1994, retired on the last
lap.
</P>
<P>
David Coulthard also from Britain, ninth starter on the grid,
spun off the track on the 21st lap.
</P>
<P>
The Spa-Francorchamps circuit once more proved to be frickle as
drivers had begun lining up on the grid for the start when the
circuit was hit by a heavy downpour.
</P>
<P>
Mechanics had already begun taking wet-weather tyres back to
pits when they were forced to ferry them back.
</P>
<P>
Organizers had no options but to start the race with the safety
car before drivers were finally let go after three laps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
