<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Exports 13.5 Million Barrels of Oil in 8 Days  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq exported more than 13.5
million barrels of crude over the past eight days under its
renewed oi-for-food deal with the United Nations, Iraqi newspaper
Al-Qadissiya said today.
</P>
<P>
This is roughly in keeping with the country's projected oil
export capacity of 1.8 million barrels a day. Iraq has to speed up
crude export to fit into a cut-off period ending December 6.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed promised that all
contracts concluded with foreign companies can be implemented
before the deadline of the second stage of the deal. By August 19
the U.N. had given green light to 22 contracts for the sale of a
total of 90.2 million barrels of Iraqi crude.
</P>
<P>
Iraq began a second six-month period of oil sales in mid-August
after a delay of more than two months while a distribution plan
for humanitarian goods was drawn up with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Oil tankers are continuing to head for the Turkish port of
Ceyhan and Iraq's Gulf port of Al-Bakr where Iraqi oil is to be
loaded.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said there is no obstacles to loading the
anchoring tankers with the amounts of oil contracted with world
companies.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage of the oil-for-food deal, Iraq managed to sell
more than 120 million barrels of its crude oil. An additional
140 million dollars of crude was also exported to purchase spare
parts for the Iraq-Turkey pipeline.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. Security Council Resolution 986, Iraq is
permitted to sell 2 billion dollars of oil over six months to
purchase humanitarian goods as well as paying reparations and the
cost of the U.N. operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the second stage, the Iraq-Turkey pipeline will export
61.3 million barrels of the oil, while its Gulf port will export
the remainder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clan Fighting Kills 7 Persons in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- At least seven people were
killed and eight others wounded on Saturday when heavy fighting
erupted between rival clan militiamen at Berhano village, 90 km
south of the port town of Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
The fighting which began two days ago escalated Saturday when
Marehan clan militiamen attacked their rival clan, Majerten, from
the south of Kismaio, 500 km south of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the field VHF radios today, the
Majerten militiamen who dominate the town of Kismaio have fought
bitterly with those of the Marehan before pushing them back to
Berhano village.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the renewed fighting is not yet known, however
the reports attributed the attack of the Marehans to a
revenge-taking measure taken by the clansmen of Marehan after two
World Concern employees were killed inside Kismaio by Majerten
gunmen four days ago.
</P>
<P>
The hostility between the two clans is now at its highest peak
since they started fighting for control of Kismaio early this
year. At least 60 people have died and more than a hundred others
were wounded so far.
</P>
<P>
There have been several peace initiatives launched by elders
from both sides and other mediatory clans in the region, but none
was fruitful as each side remained stuck on its version for their
right to control the town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
