<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Contributes to Increasing Worldwide Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Recent estimates indicate that
10 million people will die from tobacco-related diseases by the
year 2025 if current smoking patterns persist, according to
information released during the 10th World Conference on Tobacco
and Health which opened today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The total number of global deaths from tobacco will include
three million people in developed countries and seven million
people in developing countries, according to Richard Peto, a
professor from Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
Peto said that three million people throughout the world die
from smoking each year, with the number of deaths in developing
countries amounting for some 33 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Predictions for major increases in annual tobacco-related deaths
in developing countries are based partly on rapidly
growing cigarette sales in related countries, said Peto.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out China, the largest producer and consumer of
tobacco, will record between two and three million people
smoking-related deaths by the year 2025, a dramatic rise on the
half million annual deaths at present.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "prolonged smoking may eventually present the same
level of hazard in developed countries, where about half of
regular smokers die from diseases directly related to the habit."
</P>
<P>
Another report revealed that the mortality rate for female
smokers is developed countries, with the United States recording
the highest rate. The smoking mortality rate for in middle and
eastern Europe is also amongs the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Quitting smoking at the earliest possible date may help those
who have not as yet developed serious smoking-related diseases
avoid the risk of death from tobacco, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
