renewed oi-for-food deal with the United Nations, Iraqi newspaper
Al-Qadissiya said today.
</P>
<P>
This is roughly in keeping with the country's projected oil
export capacity of 1.8 million barrels a day. Iraq has to speed up
crude export to fit into a cut-off period ending December 6.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed promised that all
contracts concluded with foreign companies can be implemented
before the deadline of the second stage of the deal. By August 19
the U.N. had given green light to 22 contracts for the sale of a
total of 90.2 million barrels of Iraqi crude.
</P>
<P>
Iraq began a second six-month period of oil sales in mid-August
after a delay of more than two months while a distribution plan
for humanitarian goods was drawn up with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Oil tankers are continuing to head for the Turkish port of
Ceyhan and Iraq's Gulf port of Al-Bakr where Iraqi oil is to be
loaded.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said there is no obstacles to loading the
anchoring tankers with the amounts of oil contracted with world
companies.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage of the oil-for-food deal, Iraq managed to sell
more than 120 million barrels of its crude oil. An additional
140 million dollars of crude was also exported to purchase spare
parts for the Iraq-Turkey pipeline.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. Security Council Resolution 986, Iraq is
permitted to sell 2 billion dollars of oil over six months to
purchase humanitarian goods as well as paying reparations and the
cost of the U.N. operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the second stage, the Iraq-Turkey pipeline will export
61.3 million barrels of the oil, while its Gulf port will export
the remainder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
