<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Beat USA 3-1 in World Grand Prix Volleyball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia beat the United States 3-1
to win its ninth straight victories in the World Grand Prix
women's volleyball tournament in Gifu, Japan, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Evguenia Artamonova won eight points with her devastating
attacks and hit another 13 winners for side out to lead the
Russian spikers to a 15-9, 4-15, 15-6, 15-5 victory in one hour
and 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Today's match was very important for us to prepare for the
final round in Kobe. Our target in Kobe is to beat Cuba. It's not
easy to win the World Grand Prix, but we will play our best to
win," said Russian coach Nikolai Karpol.
</P>
<P>
In the other match at the Gifu Memorial Centre, Olympic
champions Cuba outclassed Japan 15-7, 12-15, 15-12, 15-13.
</P>
<P>
After the three qualifying rounds, Russia, South Korea and Cuba
as well as hosts Japan advanced to the four-team Grand Prix final
to be played next week in Kobe.
</P>
<P>
Russia, losers in a playoff for the bronze medal at the Atlanta
Olympics, stood atop the qualifying round with 16 points, while
Cuba ended with a 6-3 win-loss record to collect 15 points for
third place.
</P>
<P>
The third round for South Korea, China, Italy and the
Netherlands was scrapped because of the lack of a host country and
their points were multiplied by 1.5, giving South Korea second
place with 16.5 points with a 5-1 record.
</P>
<P>
China and Italy ended with 3-3 records for 13.5 points, and the
 Netherlands 1-5 for 10.5 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
