<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 700,000 Chinese To Die From Smoking-Related Diseases This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A professor from the Chinese
Academy of Preventive Medicine predicts that some 700,000 Chinese
people, including 600,000 men, will die from smoking-related
diseases this year.
</P>
<P>
During an address at today's opening meeting of the 10th World
Conference on Tobacco and Health in Beijing, Professor Niu Shiru
said that a recent national perspective study on mortality
indicated that smoking-related diseases will account for about 12
percent of the deaths of five million Chinese male adults during
1997.
</P>
<P>
Niu added that smoking-related diseases will contribute to the
deaths of over 100,000 Chinese women in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The study, which surveyed over 250,000 Chinese male adults,
showed that smokers face a much greater risk of cancer, and
respiratory system and cardio-vascular diseases than nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
Cigarette consumption in China has jumped by 30 percent in the
past 20 years, and the country is currently the world's major
producer and consumer of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Another survey released at the conference revealed that about
63 percent of Chinese male adults and four percent of Chinese
women smoke. Male and female smokers consume an average of 15 and
11 cigarettes daily.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that middle-aged and young smokers began
smoking at 20 year of age, and that the smoking rate for people
between 15-25 is growing more rapidly than for all other age
groups.
</P>
<P>
Conferees pointed out that the smoking rate for Chinese men is
much higher than rate for women, but that the latter group
nonetheless faces considerable hazards from smoking.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the rising number of young smokers and younger
starting age of smokers may greatly harm the nation's overall
health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
