<HEADLINE> South Korea Announces Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will channel 10
million U.S. dollars worth of food, medicine and farming
implements to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
the Ministry of National Unification announced over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the aid package, to be delivered through the
U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), will mainly benefit children in
DPRK.
</P>
<P>
It said the decision was made under the government's policy of
continued humanitarian assistance to the flood-and-drought
attacked DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to send farming equipment, though small in scope,
can be construed as our government's proclamation of a more active
policy to help the North (DPRK)," said Lee Jong-yul, director
general of ministry's Humanitarian Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
International relief workers estimate that about 800,000 tons
of food are needed in the DPRK before their October harvest.
</P>
<P>
The latest announcement of aid came in the wake of last
Tuesday's groundbreaking for the two 1,000-megawatt light-water
nuclear reactors to be built by the Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organization (KEDO) in Sinpo, DPRK. 
</P>
