<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia To Voice Stand in Efforts to Curb Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will voice its
stand in efforts to curb currency manipulations at the
Commonwealth Finance Ministers meeting in Mauritius next month,
its Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are firm in our stand to ensure there are joint efforts to
fight rogue speculators who meddle with international currencies,"
Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said in Pulau Pinang,
according to official media reports here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar expressed his confidence that due consideration will be
given to discuss the issue as it had "degraded the currencies of
many countries".
</P>
<P>
A series of discussions have been and will be held with the
finance ministers of the affected countries to reach a consensus
on the joint efforts to fight the speculators including U.S.
billionaire financier George Soros who allegedly had destabilized
the financial system in this region and that of several other
countries in the world, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Central Bank of Malaysia had started discussions on
the issue with the central banks of ASEAN member countries.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday, I discussed the matter with Chinese Prime Minister
Li Peng and tonight I will raise the issue with the finance
minister of Indonesia," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Anwar met the Chinese premier in Pulau Pinang, who left for
Singapore this morning following a four-day official visit in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said issues on currency manipulations are
also expected to be discussed at the ASEAN-Europe finance
ministers meeting in Bangkok and the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund annual meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
A joint strategy needs to be adopted to tackle the issue, he
stressed, adding that in fact, Malaysia had suggested several
proposals to certain countries for implementation to check
currency speculations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, upon returning to Kuala Lumpur today, Anwar said he
regretted with the allegations that his government was
over-reacting to the currency manipulation issue.
</P>
<P>
He said many countries including developed nations disagreed
with the manner in which Soros speculated on currencies but they
are not brave to voice out.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, some of the countries have asked Malaysia to speak
up. We are brave to voice our views as we are not dependent on
anybody or owe major lenders to develop the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that although Malaysia enjoyed a vibrant economy in the
past eight years, unpopular things sometimes do crop up.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken appropriate steps including stepping
up exports, minimizing imports and create various activities to
reduce the outflow of funds, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
