<HEADLINE> Nigerians Called On to Cooperate with Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha has urged Nigerians to put down confrontational
attitude and cooperate with the government in order to evolve an
enduring political culture.
</P>
<P>
"We can never make it if we continue to dissipate energy in
unnecessary confrontation," Abacha said in the capital Abuja on
Saturday, quoted by "Sunday Tribune" today.
</P>
<P>
"What we require in the days is cooperation and not
confrontation," Abacha told a funding raising ceremony of the
Alumni Association of National Institute of Policy and Strategic
Studies.
</P>
<P>
According to the head of state, the country has entered a
crucial stage of the military regime's transition to civil rule
program, both the government and Nigerians "are faced with
greater challenges of peace and stability, nation building,
democracy and development."
</P>
<P>
The military is scheduled to hand over power to an elected
civilian government in October next year, according to the
transition program of the Abacha administration.
</P>
<P>
With a little more than one year to go, there are a lot for
the administration to cope with in a view to creating an
environment favorable for a peaceful handover, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The government has over the past few years gained some
progress in macro-economic control, with foreign reserves on the
rise and inflation rate on the decline.
</P>
<P>
Political parties have been registered and are busy consulting
with the transition agencies over the democratization process.
</P>
<P>
The administration has also made efforts in the diplomatic
front, making new friends in the east while trying to improving
relations with its traditional partners in the west.
</P>
<P>
In west Africa, Nigeria's contribution to the sub-regional
efforts in ending the bloody civil war in Liberia has won the
country a good reputation and reinforced its leading role in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The urgent need of the Abacha administration at present is to
strive to convince Nigerians, and the international community as
well, of its sincere readiness to hand over to civil rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
