<HEADLINE> Foreign Capital Flows to Pudong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Major international companies
are pouring investments into the New Pudong Area which only a few
years ago was nothing more than forgotten land in the vast
metropolis of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government opened Pudong to overseas capital in
1990, and investors from over 60 foreign countries and regions
have since invested a total of 23.07 billion US dollars in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-two of the top 500 international companies have
invested in Pudong, an area covering 350 sq.km., with a number of
international giants which have moved their headquarters or
regional headquarters into Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign businessmen feel that Pudong has the greatest
potential of all of the nation's open areas and will play a role
as a bridge between the Chinese and world economies.
</P>
<P>
According to local government sources, the municipal government
of Shanghai has invested over 30 billion yuan for infrastructure
construction in Pudong in order to offer China's best investment
environment. Simple procedures make it possible for companies to
complete registration formalities in no more than 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The central government has granted Pudong a series of
preferential policies, especially in terms of foreign capital and
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Local officials from the Pudong New Area Administrative
Committee say that Pudong has entered a new stage which involves
establishing industrial zones in different sections, rather than
simply building infrastructure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
