<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Reserve 17 Percent of Land for Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government is to
reserve 17 percent of the land in the country as forest estates,
reported local daily "The Monitor" today.
</P>
<P>
Haguma Isoke, Minister of State for Natural Resources, was
quoted as announcing that " 50 percent of the percent has been
designated for production forestry and 20 percent as strict
nature reserves while the rest will remain as buffer zone where
limited production forestry will be achieved."
</P>
<P>
He added that although the government has continuously been
concerned about the state of the natural forests, destruction has
only escalated.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that 33 percent of tropical forests in
Uganda have been destroyed through agriculture, uncontrolled
human settlement and bad tree harvests.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is losing forest cover at an alarming rate. Statistics
shows that the country's forest cover has dwindled from 14
percent of its total land in 1967 to seven percent at present.
</P>
<P>
To reserve 17 percent of land for forests is part of draft
national nature conservation master plan whose work started in
1987, the report revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
