<HEADLINE> Memorial Pavilion Built to Mark HK's Return to Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A memorial pavilion to mark
the return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1, 1997 was
unveiled here today.
</P>
<P>
Situated on Lion Rock Hill in Kowloon, the hexagonal pavilion
commands a good view of the Hong Kong Island, the Kowloon
Peninsula and the Victoria Harbor, the world busiest seaport.
</P>
<P>
A non-government organization in Kowloon raised nearly 700,000
HK dollars (about 90,000 US dollars) to build the pavilion, hoping
that later generations will always bear in mind the historic
moment, when China resumed its exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
A horizontal board hung inside the pavilion features
inscription of Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), reading "Hong Kong
Reunification Memorial Pavilion".
</P>
<P>
It took a couple of months to complete the construction,
according to the organization, which was formed by various sectors
in Kowloon to celebrate the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
For hikers, this traditional Chinese architecture provides a
shelter from the tropical rain and sunshine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
