<HEADLINE> S. African Schools Face Textbook Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cutbacks, delays and other problems are also causing chaos in
the country's publishing industry, which depends on textbooks for
half its volume of work and many are floundering financially, the
report quoted informed sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last year's spending on textbooks in South Africa was slashed
by 42 percent to around 520 million Rand (111 million U.S.
Dollars) from 895 million Rand (190 million U.S.Dollars) in
1995/96, despite the fact that only 49 percent of schools are
currently adequately provided with textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Publishers still have no idea how much provinces will spend on
books in the current financial year. But it is likely that cuts
to provincial budget allocations will substantially reduce
textbook spending once again, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the problem, newly-elected Chairman of the South
African Publishers' Assoiciation Kate Mccallum said: "We are
seriously concerned about the supply of textbooks to schools in
1998."  
</P>
