<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Lags Behind in Internet Race: German HP Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Germans have tend to be too
suspicious of the commercial development of the Internet computer
network, thus falling far behind in its commercial use, the German
subsidiary of the U.S. computer giant Hewlett-Packard (HP) said
today.
</P>
<P>
While German companies were generally interested in the
potential of the Internet as a business tool, they've been
relatively slow to adopt it, said Joerg Menno Harms, head of the
HP's German subsidiary, in an interview with the German news
agency DPA.
</P>
<P>
Currently in Europe, Britain and the Scandinavian countries
have the highest rate of Internet use per capita, said Harms,
adding that this will probably not change within the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
But European countries in general are still lagging far behind
in the use of Internet in comparison with the United States, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to his estimates, European commerical transactions
over the Internet will reach about 7 billion U.S. dollars annually
by the year of 2000. While two thirds of that volume would come
from Britain and Scandinavia, Germany will have a relatively
modest share of about 10 percent, he predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
