<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Expand Offset Program to Civil Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is to expand its
Offset program to oblige foreign civil contractors, like their
military counterparts, to reinvest in the country or its overseas
projects.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuwaiti Finance Minister Nasser Al-Roudhan today,
a plan to bring civil supplies contract under the Offset program
is now under consideration.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait started its Offset program in 1992 under a Cabinet
decision stipulating that foreign companies which sign contracts
with the Kuwaiti government in the military field worth 3.3
million U.S. dollars or above are obliged to reinvest an
equivalent up to 30 percent of the contractual value.
</P>
<P>
The amounts should be invested either in the country or in its
abroad projects to contribute to the country's economy, according
to the program.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the base for implementing the Offset program
will obviously bring more benefit to the country, but it's too
early to predict if this would affect the enthusiasm of foreign
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti minister told local daily Arab Times in an
interview published today that a foreign company which he did not
name and recently had a supplies contract with the Kuwaiti
Ministry of Electricity and Water was obliged to join the program.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al-Roudhan said that Kuwait has attained potential
projects valued at 1.5 billion dollars which have to be
implemented by companies under the program.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that not all the obligations have been met so
far, and urged foreign companies falling to abide by the
conditions set by the program even if they do not have any
immediate projects for implementation.
</P>
<P>
He said "some penalties are imposed in respect of companies
which failed to comply with the specified time schedule stipulated
to come up with various projects to enable them to fulfill their
obligations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
