<HEADLINE> S. African Defense Minister Ends Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 24 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise left here today, wrapping up a two-day visit
for the promotion of sale of Pretoria-made weapons.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Kuwait News Agency today, during his
stay here the minister held talks with Kuwaiti leaders on a
possible sale of self-propelled howitzers to the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial sources said Modise, who arrived here late Friday,
was trying to persuade the Kuwaiti leaders to arm a proposed new
battalion with the South African guns.
</P>
<P>
He met Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah and acting
Prime Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, but there was no
official word on the agenda of their talks.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency reports said they held talks on bilateral
relations and issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said Pretoria offered to sell to Kuwait LIW
155mm G6 self-propelled howitzers. The deal is expected to be
worth hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both the U.S. and Britain want to sell their own
arms to the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
This was the first visit to the Gulf Arab state by a South
African defense minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
