<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Phones Albright to Complain About PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu telephoned U.S. States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright overnight to complain about the Palestinian
National Authority's (PNA) reluctance on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports today, Netanyahu said during the
phone conversation that PNA President Yasser Arafat was not
honoring the agreements reached with U.S. special peace envoy
Dennis Ross earlier this month by failing to carry out the
commitment to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's recent meetings with leaders of Palestinian
opposition groups, including the Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) and Islamic Jihad, would not contribute to the peace
process, Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiation between Israel and the Palestinians have been
frozen since March when Israel began building the controversial
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem in spite of strong warnings
from the PNA and outcry in the world.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, on the other hand, also called up Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King Hussein to warn that the peace
process was in danger unless there was a real change in Arafat's
stance toward Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu demanded that Arafat crack down on the militant
Islamic groups and their support infrastructure, by rounding up
extremist activists, disarming them and cutting off their funding.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements reached during Ross' visit, the PNA
promised to resume security cooperation with Israel and fight
terrorism to pave the way for the maiden visit to the region by
Albright late August or early September.
</P>
<P>
But the PNA has repeatedly urged in vain Israel to lift its
sanctions imposed after the July 30 Jerusalem market bombings,
which include total closure of Palestinian-controlled areas, ban on
Palestinian workers from entering Israel and freeze of the tax
revenues due to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
In a gesture to reward the partial security cooperation from
Palestinian police in the bombing investigation and the arrest of
three Palestinian murderers of an Israeli taxi driver, Israeli
government released last week only one-third of a total 14 million
dollars in tax revenues collected by the Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his anger and despair about "Israeli arrogance,"
Arafat started a two-day dialogue last Wednesday in Gaza and
Ramallah with Palestinian opposition groups within the framework
of "national unity forum."
</P>
<P>
Israel strongly denounced Arafat for trying to appease and
placate the militant groups in an attempt to exert pressure on
Israel, thus breaching the agreements reached during Ross'
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
