<HEADLINE> S. Africa Considers Parliament Moving Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A formal recommendation to
move South African parliament to Pretoria is currently considered
by a special working committee of the ruling African National
Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
Under the recommendation, parliament will be moved to Pretoria
from Cape Town and the Parliamentary Complex will be sold for
some 58 million U.S. Dollars, a local newspaper "City Press"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the ANC's top policy-making body, the National
Executive Committee (NEC), will discuss the proposal in October.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was presented to the NEC last month by a
team consisting two ministers and deputy parliament speaker.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation is based on a set of Ministry of Public
Works memoranda in which it is stated that the country could save
millions of fund if parliament was moved.
</P>
<P>
The memoranda state that parliament can be housed in existing
state buildings in Pretoria, South Africa's administrative
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
