<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Boom Expected in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will earn about 19
billion Shillings (about 300 million Dollars) through coffee sale
this year due to high quality and favorable prices in the world
markets, the Kenya Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Roughly 80,000 tons of coffee is expected to be sold at the
end of 1996/97 financial year which ends on September 31, the
report quoted Peter Michoru, Director of the Coffee Research
Foundation of Kenya, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kenya sold 90,000 tons of coffee but only collected 16 billion
Shillings (about 260 million Dollars) from the sale in the
previous financial year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The fall in coffee yield this year is caused by severe drought
which hit most parts of the country early this year, said
Michoru.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenyan coffee has been regarded as one of the best
quality in the world market, enabling the eastern African country
to earn a lot of money, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
