<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks to Open as Sheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi peace talks
will open on Monday though it was said to be cancelled after the
Burundian government demanded for a postponement, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The talks will start as originally scheduled in the northern
Tanzanian Town of Arusha but without the participation of the
Burundi government team, said the report, quoting an aide of
former Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere who is the
international facilitator on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the organizers said that they had reversed a
decision on Friday to cancel the talks after they realized it was
too late to recall some delegations already heading for the
venue.
</P>
<P>
The aide of Nyerere said, "He (Nyerere) just regrets the
government delegation of Burundi will not be attending (the
talks)."
</P>
<P>
The talks were planned to bring together the government and
the main Hutu rebel group the National Council for the Defense of
Democracy for the first time in a public forum.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi government said earlier on Saturday it only wanted
the peace talks postponed for two weeks or less and was trying to
contact Nyerere to set a new date for the talks. The Burundi
government's request was said on the grounds that successful
talks were unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Observers, however, are of the view that the absence of a
Burundi government delegation means little progress could be made
to end the civil war and the political crisis in Burundi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
