<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why IMF Aid Fails to Prop Up Baht? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai currency of baht
continued to weaken against the U.S. dollar despite the
International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s approval of a standby credit
of 3.9 billion U.S. dollars for Thailand last Wednesday. The baht
was once sold at more than 34 baht to the dollar on Thursday,
hitting a record low.
</P>
<P>
The IMF aid is part of international rescue package totaling
more than 16 billion dollars to help Thailand to revive its ailing
economy and reinforce its foreign exchange reserves to stabilize
the country shaky financial sector.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF assistance seemed too small to immediately
bring about a good news to the baht as the country has a worse
news heard.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank Wednesday disclosed for the first time
that Thailand had commitments totaling 23.4 billion dollars in
outstanding currency forward obligations over the next 12 months,
which may suggest that the country's foreign reserves had been
significantly drained during its mid-May battle in defending the
baht.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures published earlier by the central bank,
Thailand's foreign reserves stood at above 37 billion dollars
before May, but the figure dropped to 32.4 billion dollars at the
end of June.
</P>
<P>
Analysts previously believed that Thailand only spent a maximum
of 5 billion dollars in its counter-attacks against speculations
on the baht in mid-May this year.
</P>
<P>
Yet the latest disclosure of Thailand's outstanding currency
debts sent a surprise to the financial markets, fueling the bath
down to the record low recently.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank Wednesday said in a letter of intent that
as of August 19, Thailand had currency forward obligations
totaling 23.4 billion dollars over the next 12 months. Of this
amount, 8.6 billion dollars was for onshore activities related to
domestic monetary operations and 14.8 billion dollars was for
offshore activities.
</P>
<P>
Onshore activities are instruments of domestic liquidity
management, which have since last year become part of the normal
conduct of monetary operations. The central bank undertakes daily
auctions of swap transactions with domestic financial institutions
as a way of providing baht liquidity.
</P>
<P>
This part of the operation is normally rolled over and will not
adversely affect Thailand's foreign reserves position, the central
bank said.
</P>
<P>
The offshore activities are interventions in defending the baht
against intensive speculative attacks, it explained.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding forward debts have been taken into account when
Thailand held consultations with the IMF on international rescue
aid, so Thailand set targets to maintain its foreign reserves at
the level of 23 billion dollars for 1997 and 25 billion dollars
for 1998, the central bank noted.
</P>
<P>
The huge outstanding forward obligations disclosed by the
central bank are triggering speculations on Thailand's real
foreign reserves position.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that people could not believe that
Thailand's foreign reserves has dropped to 9 billion dollars
simply by deducting the forward debts from the June reserves
figure of 32.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding forward obligations will be delivered at a set
date in the future and some of them will be rolled over, they
added.
</P>
<P>
In an overall view, the huge outstanding forward debts are
hurting the market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the limited IMF aid currently help little in
restoring investors' confidence in Thailand's foreign reserves
position and the baht is expected to further weaken over the next
days or weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
