<HEADLINE> Gujral Unlikely to Meet Clinton in New York: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral is unlikely to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton
during his New York visit next month, the Financial Express
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Gujral is scheduled to address the 52nd session of the United
Nations General assembly on September 30 and it may not be
possible to advance his visit to New York by a week to be there on
September 23, official sources was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports from Washington, Clinton has offered
to have bilateral discussion with Gujral during a day-long visit
to the UN on September 23.
</P>
<P>
The official line of thinking here was reported to be that the
Indian government has already established high-level contact with
the Clinton administration during the last few months.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for External Affairs Saleem Shervani recently
met U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at the ASEAN
regional forum meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, last month.
Albright has also promised to visit India later this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, new U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for South
Asia, Karl Inderfurth, is scheduled to visit India next month,
which may be followed by a visit by Thomas Picketing, under
secretary of state for political affairs.
</P>
<P>
These visits will enable the two countries to exchange views on
a wide-range of issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
In view of these developments, it was felt there is no need for
Gujral to reschedule his New York visit for a half-an-hour meeting
with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
But one report carried by the Times of India today said that
efforts are still on to strike out an arrangement for a
Gujral-Clinton meet in New York.  
</P>
