<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Opposition Calls Strike Against Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's opposition political
parties called a dawn-to-dusk countrywide general strike today in
protest against the price hike of petrol and petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP),
Jamaat-e-Islami and the dissident faction of Jatiya (national)
Party enforced the strike separately, as the government rejected
their call to rescind its decision on the fuel price hike.
</P>
<P>
Due to enhanced prices on the international market and pressure
by donor agencies, the government on August 18 raised the prices
of all petroleum products, among which price of petrol has been
raised by over 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sudden price hike sparked off street protests by opposition
groups and transport unions. A partial transport strike is still
going on in capital Dhaka and other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, argued that the price-hike will not
affect the common people including farmers and transport sectors
as the increase in the prices of diesel and kerosene is nominal.
</P>
<P>
"The government has proved to be a complete failure in running
the state affairs and resolving people's problems in last 14
months," the BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia said in a statement
calling for the general strike.
</P>
<P>
In support of the today's strike, the BNP and its front
organizations Saturday held rallies and brought out various
processions in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The opposition activists allegedly set fire to some vehicles
and damaged some others during the procession.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a BNP statement issued Saturday night claimed at
least eight BNP workers were injured when the ruling party
activists swooped down their rally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
