<HEADLINE> Rains Claim over 50 in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 people, including
three children and two women, were killed in heavy rains and
floods that battered Indian states of Maharashtra and West Bengal
for the second day on Saturday, the Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
While 23 persons died in Maharashtra cities such as Bombay and
Pune, the toll in Midnapore district of West Bengal reached 34,
including 18 people claimed by snake-bites.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, nearly 400 fishermen of Midnapore district who had
gone for deep sea fishing on Wednesday were still reported
missing.
</P>
<P>
According to local weather bureau, heavy rains continued in the
northern suburbs of Bombay on Saturday, but receded in other
parts.
</P>
<P>
The suburban railway services in the commercial capital of
India were disrupted for the second consecutive day on Saturday.
Flood water at some stations ranged between eight inches and 48
inches.
</P>
<P>
Several parts of the city experienced blackouts as electricity
cables got waterlogged. Wall collapses were reported in several
parts of the metropolitan city.
</P>
<P>
In Pune, another major city of Maharashtra, about 10,000 people
were rendered homeless.  
</P>
