<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Launch Business Could Skyrocket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China consolidated its position
in the global commercial satellite launching market after a
successful flight last week, the "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The China Great Wall Industry Corp. sent a Philippino
telecommunications satellite into orbit on Wednesday using a Long
March 3B rocket.
</P>
<P>
It was the first successful Long March 3B flight after an
abortive attempt 18 months ago. That was the first time the
company tried to launch a Long March 3B satellite.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Ukraine and Japan are major rivals trying to challenge
France's dominant position.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders said Wednesday's flight, as well as three
successful launches since last October, have restored public
confidence in LM launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Long March 3B rockets can carry satellites as heavy as 5,000
kilograms. Most of the world's satellites weigh no more than 4,500
kgs.
</P>
<P>
The Philippino satellite, made by US-based Space System Loral,
is one of high-power communications satellites which are expected
to become popular in the next few years. The satellites are
launched into geosynchronous transfer orbit (GTO).
</P>
<P>
About 25 GTO satellites are launched annually worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said his company could clinch two or four GTO contracts
with foreign companies each year after 1997, now that the Long
March 3B has proven successful.
</P>
<P>
China covered less than nine percent of the global GTO market
from 1990 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's company lost several contracts after it failed to send
a satellite into orbit in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's launch was the first successful co-operation
between CGWIC and Loral.
</P>
<P>
While securing a stable share of the GTO satellite market,
China plans to take on low- and medium-orbit business.
</P>
<P>
Satellites orbiting the earth from about 1,000 to 10,000
kilometres away are used for mobile communications and interactive
communication networks.
</P>
<P>
About 600 or 700 lower-orbit satellites will be launched
worldwide by 2006, creating great opportunities for China's Long
March rockets, which can carry satellites as heavy as nine tons.
</P>
<P>
The LM-2C/SD launch vehicle has been developed for low earth
orbit. It will be used to launch IRIDIUM satellites according to a
contract between CGWIC and Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
This new device evolves from the LM-2C with new smart
dispensers.
</P>
<P>
CGWIC also plans to co-operate with foreign partners in
satellite applications and components.
</P>
<P>
Companies from the United States and Europe might be major
potential partners, but the United Sates has restricted its
companies by controlling high-tech exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
