<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slack Sales Drive Record Low Car Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Car imports are the lowest in
ten years because of fierce competition and government crack-downs
on illegal assembly of foreign-produced parts, the "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, the auto import volume was 770
million US dollars, down 23.3 percent from the same period last
year. Exports rose 16.7 percent from the same period last year,
hitting 376 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China imported 13,700 cars during that period, down 60 percent
in number and value.
</P>
<P>
"The market potential is huge, but demand is relatively weak,"
said Chen Ping, vice-president of the China Trading Centre for
Automobile Import (CTCAI).
</P>
<P>
She said most imported cars had engines ranging from 1.6 litres
to 2.0 litres, triggering a clash with domestically made
small-engine car makers.
</P>
<P>
Firm State measures to curtail car body and parts imports have
curbed illegal car assembly.
</P>
<P>
This year, CTCAI imported no cars, and its sole business was
selling hundreds of unsold sedans imported last year.
</P>
<P>
"We act as only a regulator in the market, rather than seeking
exorbitant profits," Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
