<HEADLINE> State Mulls Direct Bond Issue Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China is considering allowing
large State enterprises to conduct direct overseas financing --
including bond issues in the international capital market and
foreign commercial loans, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The measure is aimed at creating new fund raising methods for
Chinese firms that are striving to reform their operations as the
country's market economy takes off.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Administration of Foreign Exchange
(SAFE) said many firms applied for direct overseas financing
permission. Some have good credit ratings from international
rating companies.
</P>
<P>
The official said SAFE and the State Planning Commission were
studying the conditions and qualifications for overseas bond issues
by State firms.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing firms to issue bonds overseas is something to come
sooner or later," he said. "But the timetable will be fixed by
the State Council."
</P>
<P>
The official said firms build up their worldwide reputations
through bond issues and learn more about international financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
"The bond issue will make firms adapt to the international
market more quickly and increase their competitiveness," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
