<HEADLINE> Argentina, Brazil Deny Discord over U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASUNCION, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports of a row between
Argentina and Brazil over Brazil's bid for the United Nations
Security Council permanent member status, the two countries'
presidents today denied that any problem has cropped up in their
relations.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem and his Brazilian counterpart
Fernando Henrique Cardoso said during the Rio Group summit, which
opened here today, that there are no problems between the two
neighbors and they would solve any differences through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Argentina reportedly opposed Brazil's application for a
permanent seat in the U.N. Security Council, fearing it would
shatter "regional balance."
</P>
<P>
Menem said that the two nations are having dialogue on the
reform of the U.N. Security Council, including the voice and veto
of the council's members.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no problems in bilateral ties as all topics
concerning the consolidation of the Mercosur and the Latin
American integration are under discussion.
</P>
<P>
"And for any problems that could emerge, we try to find their
solution beforehand," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents, participating the two-day summit, said that
there is nothing more important than maintaining a good
understanding and unity between the two countries, major partners
in the booming regional bloc of the South American Common Market
(Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said the two countries consider as priorities the
strengthening of the Mercosur, which also groups Uruguay and
Paraguay, and the economic growth of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The Rio Group, founded in 1986 to coordinate member nations'
political and economic policies, embraces Argentina, Bolivia,
Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Mexico, Panama, Paraguay, Peru,
Uruguay and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
