<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Stress Significant to Grain Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China intends to make
agri-science support its growing population early in the next
century, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The country will have nearly 1.6 billion people by 2030 and
will need 640 million tons of grain a year.
</P>
<P>
The grain output last year was a record high of 490 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
"Although we can increase 500 million tons of grain by 2000
with available technology, we cannot secure another 150 million
tons from 2000 to 2030 without new breakthroughs," said an
official from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In the first 30 years of the next century, China will have to
increase its grain production capacity by 50 million tons every 10
years to feed a growing population, the official said.
</P>
<P>
As the world's most populous nation, China has endless
difficulties expanding arable land. "Science is the key," she
said. "The only way out for China's agriculture is a scientific
revolution."
</P>
<P>
Science constitutes 39 percent of China's grain output. She
said the proportion would be 50 percent y by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In developed countries, 70 or 80 percent of grain production
results from scientific progress.
</P>
<P>
The main task until 2000 will be to spread current agriculture
technology. From 2000 to 2020, China should strive to make
breakthroughs in the cultivation of super breeds of rice, corn and
wheat, as well as use water, fertilizer and soil resources more
efficiently. By 2030, China will have to make breakthroughs in
biological technology to sustain agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
The official said China was accelerating research of high-yield
rice breeds, planting corn in the south, improving wheat quality
and spreading winter wheat to the north.
</P>
<P>
A super rice breed is being developed, but will not be applied
nationwide until for several years, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium's Foreign Trade Jumps in First 5 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade has increased
considerably in Belgium in the first five months of this year,
with import and export jumping 9.7 percent and 11.2 percent
respectively over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that Belgium's total import volume for the
period stood at 2,273 billion Belgium francs, or 65 billion
U.S. dollars, export volume at 2,417 billion Belgium francs, or 70
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
With only a population of 10 million, Belgium ranks the world's
10th biggest country in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country's total export stood at 158 billion
dollars, the biggest per capita export in the world.
</P>
<P>
Europe is still Belgium's top foreign market, accounting for 82
percent of its total export, followed by Asia and America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
