<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Solar Energy Demonstration School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Asia's first rural solar
energy pilot school has been established in Mancheng
County, north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation's Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) helped to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO and the China Assoc. for Science and Technology selected
the Lingxi Middle School in the Taihang Mountains as the 21st
century solar energy pilot school. The project was carried out as
part of the "1996-2005 Global Solar Energy Plan."
</P>
<P>
The school has 500 students. Lying in a remote area, it used to
suffer from serious electricity shortages.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO provided 30,000 US dollars for the project, with local
governments contributing 450,000 yuan (54,000 US dollars). The
school complex includes a four-kw solar energy power station,
solar powered houses, bathrooms and stoves, as well as audio-video
teaching facilities.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that solar energy applications could be
used to solve power supply problems in some underdeveloped areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
