<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Cotton Field Insured Against Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Cotton on a wide expanse of
farmland in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has
been insured against natural disasters, according to a regional
source.
</P>
<P>
Growers of the cotton, planted across an area of more than 13
million mu (about 860,000 ha), can get up to 10 million yuan
(about 1.2 million US dollars) in indemnity if their crop is hit
by natural adversities.
</P>
<P>
When plant disease and insects ravaged the crop during last
year's warm winter and the dry spell early this year, the Xinjiang
branch of the People's Insurance Company of China (Property), the
property insurance arm of China's leading insurer, paid more than
three million yuan in special funds to 44 cotton-growing counties,
effectively helping to curb the spread of harmful insects.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the regional insurance company has paid a
total of 80 million yuan in indemnity to overcome the effects of
snowstorms, floods and hail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
