<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More inquiry Urged Into Misconducts of Italian Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Italian Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta today called for reopening the investigation into the
alleged misconducts of Italian peacekeepers in Somalia as new
evidence came into light.
</P>
<P>
The commission led by the former Constitutional Court chief
Ettore Gallo should be reopened to do fresh investigation into the
allegations, Andreatta said.
</P>
<P>
On August 9, the commission ended six weeks of inquiry on the
alleged torture of Somali citizens by Italian troops on a UN
peacekeeping mission in Somalia from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
While concluding that isolated instances of torture did occur,
it cleared top ranking officers of all blame.
</P>
<P>
A 170-page diary kept by Italian officer Francesco Aloi between
May and July 1993 was brought into light recently and it lists
atrocities committed against the Somali civilian population by
Italian peacekeepers, including murder and rape.
</P>
<P>
With the new evidence, the reopening of the investigation will
be "extremely useful" and the commission should take up its
investigation again into the case as further serious indications
of misconduct had emerged, Andreatta said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
