<HEADLINE> Hakkinen Put Back of Grid for Using Illegal Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Finn driver Mika Hakkinen of
Mclaren-Mercedes, was put back of the grid Saturday for Sunday's
Belgian Grand Prix for using illegal fuel.
</P>
<P>
Race officials also fined Hakkinen's team 25,000 U.S. dollars
after ruling that fuel in his car had been found not to conform
with samples submitted before the event.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen had set the time in an effort called "exceptional" by
team boss Ron Dennis, after a serious accident in the morning
practice.
</P>
<P>
The decision advanced all the drivers behind Hakkinen up one
place, starting with Ralf Schumacher (Jordan Peugeot), now in
fifth place.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen had originally been set to start on the third row with
Germany's Ralf Schumacher of Jordan-Peugeot after Saturday's
official qualifying after clocking one minute 50.503 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Villeneuve of Canada, second behind Michael Schumacher
in the driver's championship, is on pole in a Williams-Renault
after clocking a fastest time of 1:49.50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
