<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Metallurgical Industry Stresses Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's metallurgical industry
will concentrate on improving its product structure, rather than
striving for increased output, according to Liu Qi, minister of
the Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
China set a world record with steel production reaching 101.23
million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua, Liu said China
plans to raise its per worker output of iron and steel from the
current 58 tons to 100 tons by the year 2000. China will
concentrate on producing steel with a high added value which will
be in great demand in the remaining years of the century.
</P>
<P>
Liu said China will try to raise the current ratio of 38 percent
of plates, sheets, strip products and rolled steel to 41 percent to
meet the market demand.
</P>
<P>
He added that the industry's continuous casting ratio, one of
the major indicators of the metallurgical industry's technical
development level, stands at 60 percent and will be raised to the
world average of 80 percent by 2000, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
China has won a victory in reducing the number of iron and
steel plants and concentrating the industry's production in fewer
companies, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five iron and steel plants currently each produce more
than one million tons annually. He said the plants account for 70
percent of the national output and 69 percent of the metallurgical
industry's assests.
</P>
<P>
Liu noted that "a number of small plants with outdated blast
furnaces and backward technology have been closed down over the
past five years."
</P>
<P>
China will continue to support the realignment of iron and
steel plants, Liu said, adding that roughly half of the nation's
nearly four million metallurgical workers can be declared
redundant.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, 49 major companies reduced their workforces by
60 percent, with redundant workers finding new jobs in the service
sector. Liu pointed out that the rest of the redundant workers
will find new jobs within the year.
</P>
<P>
Liu admitted that China's metallurgical industry faces an
uphill battle in efforts to achieve its ambitious goal of
producing more products with a high added value over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the industry has encountered difficulties in
soaring energy costs, falling prices for steel products and
intense market competition, particularly at a time when foreign
companies are trying to grab a bigger share of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that Chinese companies currently occupy 91
percent of the market in terms of tonnage, but hold a mere 82
percent market share in terms of turnover.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who became the minister in 1993 after working many years
as an engineer and later as general manager of the Wuhan Iron and
Steel Company, expressed optimism over the industry's future.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "the next few years will be a vital period
in which China's metallurgical industry will achieve technological
upgrading."
</P>
<P>
He concluded by saying that "China will become a powerful iron
and steel producer both in terms of tonnage and quality,"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popov Wins Third Gold at European Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian swimmer Alexander Popov,
invincible for the past six years, collected his third gold medal
at the European swimming championships with a typically smooth
victory in the men's 50 meters freestyle in Seville, Spain on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
One year on from the night he was stabbed by a water-melon
seller on a Moscow street, Popov serenely maintained his record of
winning all his major championship freestyle races since his debut
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Popov, who has also won his fourth European 100 freestyle title
and led Russia to victory in the 4x100 freestyle relay, swung
clear in the second half of the one-length sprint to win in 22.30
seconds, the best time in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Mark Foster, world short-course 50 freestyle champion
in 1993, took the silver in 22.53 and Frenchman Julien Sicot the
bronze in 22.78.
</P>
<P>
It was a great day for the older generation, with three
swimmers more venerable than the seasoned Popov claiming gold in
the San Pablo pool.
</P>
<P>
The most loudly acclaimed winner was Spain's Martin Lopez
Zubero, born and based in the United States, but a Spanish
national hero since his Olympic 200 backstroke victory at the 1992
Barcelona Games.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old, clinched his fourth European 100 meters
backstroke title. Trailing seventh at the turn, he accelerated on
the second length to win in a modest 55.71 from Eithan Urbach, who
clinched Israel's first-ever European championship medal with a
silver in 55.88, and Russia's 200 backstroke gold medallist
Vladimir Selkov (55.97).
</P>
<P>
Franck Esposito recaptured the 200 meters butterfly crown he
won in 1991, surging through on the last half-length to overtake
Ukraine's Denis Silantiev for the gold.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Frenchman, bronze medallist to Silantiev's
silver in Wednesday's 100 butterfly, won by the handsome margin of
1.24 seconds in 1:57.24 to consign the Ukrainian to his second
silver.
</P>
<P>
Olympic and world champion Denis Pankratov, who had won the
European crown in 1993 and 1995, failed to make the final,
finishing 11th overall in the heats, nearly two seconds behind
Esposito.
</P>
<P>
The fourth vintage winner was 27-year-old Kerstin Kielgass, who
gained compensation for the loss of her 200 freestyle crown to
Ireland's Michelle de Bruin by winning the women's 800 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Kielgass overtook Dutch pace-setter Carla Geurts in the second
half of the race to win in 8:34.41 from Geurts (8:36.14) and
fellow former East German Jana Henke (8:39.93).
</P>
<P>
Oxana Verevka, at 20 the youngest of the day's individual
champions, won the women's 200 individual medley in the absence of
Olympic champion De Bruin, who decided not to defend her European
crown because she was tired out after winning two golds and a
silver in three days.
</P>
<P>
Verevka, born in Ukraine but now competing for Russia, took the
lead from Martina Moravcova on the second length -- the backstroke
leg -- and built a big enough lead to resist a storming freestyle
finish from the Slovak swimmer, who had to settle for her third
silver medal of the championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
