<HEADLINE> Greece, FYROM Agree to Strengthen Cultural Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece and the Former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) today agreed to strengthen the
cultural cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued on the fringes of the seventh
Prespian'97 cultural festival today, Greece's Culture Minister
Evangelos Venizelos and his FYROM counterpart, Slobodan Unkofski,
said that they intended to launch "a lasting and systematic, yet
unofficial cooperation" in the sector of cultural creativity
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both ministers stressed the need of strengthening cultural
cooperation between Greece and FYROM.
</P>
<P>
Venizelos said that culture was the most useful means to create
common understanding in the world.
</P>
<P>
In response, Unkofski said that it would take a long time for
the two countries to solve the name problem, but this did not mean
that cultural cooperation should not begin between the two
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Greece and FYROM are locked in an argument over the
name of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Greece opposes the use of the name Macedonia or its derivative
by Skopje on the grounds that it harbors territorial designs
against its northern region of the same name. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
