<HEADLINE> Suspected Fish-killer Found in U.S. Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. researchers have found
in the St. Johns River in Florida the same microorganism that
exists in North Carolina's Neuse River and Maryland's Pocomoke
River, where thousands of fish have died recently.
</P>
<P>
The dinoflagelate, which does not yet have a name in English,
was discovered by researchers from St. Petersburg's Florida Marine
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Scientists wonder if the one-celled organism, about the size of
a bacteria, is responsible for lesions found on fish in the
affected waterways. They have yet to learn if the microorganism is
toxic or whether it poses a public health risk.
</P>
<P>
Trout with open sores on their gills, mouths, heads, and lower
bodies were found around the same stretch of the St. Johns River
in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
