<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Launch Spacecraft for Solar Storm Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States will launch
a scientific spacecraft worth 111 million U.S. dollars to provide an
early warning against solar storms.
</P>
<P>
The spacecraft, which is called the Advanced Composition
Explorer(ACE), was scheduled for blast-off from Cape Canaveral Air
Station atop a Boeing Delta II rocket at 10:41 a.m. EDT on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
ACE will be positioned 1.6 million km above the Earth. It will
provide a 30 to 60 minute warning before a potentially dangerous
solar storm strikes the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Eruptions on the surface of the sun can disrupt the Earth's
magnetic field, knocking out electrical power and endangering
space-walking astronauts in orbit.
</P>
<P>
The ACE spacecraft's primary purpose is to sample the high
energy matter from the sun, the space between stars and from the
Milky Way that comes close to the Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970824.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President On Speedy Foreign Trade Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that "fast track" approach is needed to make U.S.
companies more competitive worldwide and he will ask U.S. Congress
to renew his authority for speedy negotiation of trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
He said in his weekly radio address that 25 percent of U.S.
economic growth now comes from overseas trade, and U.S. exports
support more than 11 million "good, high-paying American jobs,"
including one of every five manufacturing positions.
</P>
<P>
"To keep our economy growing and to create these good jobs, we
must keep tearing down foreign barriers to American goods and
services," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't seize these new opportunities, our competitors
surely will," Clinton said. He said he wants to use trade talks to
broaden U.S. access to markets in Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fast track authority to enter into trade agreements has been
held by presidents since 1974, but that authority will expire
unless it is renewed next month.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that other nations have already negotiated 20
trade agreements in Latin America and Asia and the United
States risks being left behind unless he is given authority to
reach trade agreements without burdensome delays.
</P>
<P>
"We have to continue to create high-wage jobs, and to do that
we must continue to expand American exports," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has promised to expand the current North American Free
Trade Agreement covering Mexico and Canada by creating a
hemisphere-wide free trade area by 2005. He also has committed to
reaching a free trade deal with Pacific Rim nations by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
